The user is pointing out that lint-guard didn't run after I patched the orchestrator.ts file. Let me think about why.

Looking at the lint-guard code, it hooks into the `tool_result` event for `edit` and `write` tools:

```js
pi.on("tool_result", async (event, ctx) => {
    if (!autoLint) return;
    if (event.toolName !== "edit" && event.toolName !== "write") return;
    ...
});
```

But I used the `bash` tool (via `sed -i ''`) to make the changes! The `edit` tool would fire `tool_result` with `toolName === "edit"`, but I used `bash` which runs a shell command. So the lint-guard extension never saw the edit.

The lint-guard only triggers on `edit` and `write` tool calls from the agent. When I use `bash` to run `sed`, it's a `bash` tool execution, not an `edit` tool execution.

Also, I called `edit` tool earlier for the orchestrator changes (the first batch). But then I used `sed` via `bash` for the `pi.setHeader` fix. Those `sed` commands bypassed lint-guard because they were `bash` tool calls.

Let me explain this to the user.

